Predictors of National Carbon Dioxide Emissions

by Nat Goodby & James Valadez

Are urbanization rates and GDP predictors of a countrys carbon dioxide emmissions?

The data comes from the CIA World Factbook Data was cleaned in Python. That process can be seen here

Lets call the data:

dataLink="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ngoodby/Final_Project_James_Nat/master/Data/Cleaned_Data.csv"
df=read.csv(dataLink,stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

And look at the contents:

Lets get a sense of how far outlying Gibraltars CO2 Emissions are:

plot(df$Urbanization_Percentage,df$CO2_Emissions_PerCapita)

Would be more helpful to see this plot without Gibraltar. Lets locate it, drop it, and save the resulting dataframe:

df[76,]
##      Country CO2_Emissions_Number Urbanization_Percentage
## 76 Gibraltar             13340000                     100
##    GDP_Per_Capita_Number Population_Number CO2_Emissions_PerCapita
## 76                 61700             29461                 452.802
df_noGib=df[-76, ]

Now what does that look like if we plot again:

plot(df_noGib$Urbanization_Percentage,df_noGib$CO2_Emissions_PerCapita)

plot(df_noGib$GDP_Per_Capita_Number,df_noGib$CO2_Emissions_PerCapita)

Looks like there are higher CO2 emissions per capita as Urbanization rates and GDP per capita increase but lets look at the correlation strength:

cor(df_noGib$Urbanization_Percentage, df_noGib$CO2_Emissions_PerCapita)
## [1] 0.499226
cor(df_noGib$GDP_Per_Capita_Number, df_noGib$CO2_Emissions_PerCapita)
## [1] 0.7346852

GDP_Per_Capita is showing higher correlation with CO2 Emissions.

test1=lm(as.numeric(Urbanization_Percentage)~CO2_Emissions_PerCapita,data=df_noGib)
summary(test1)

GDP per capita shows a higher correlation (adjusted R-squared of 0.54) with CO2 emissions than Urbanization percentage did. Looking at how both independent varibles affect CO2 emissions collectively:

test3=lm(CO2_Emissions_PerCapita ~ GDP_Per_Capita_Number + Urbanization_Percentage, data=df_noGib)
summary(test3)
